<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1438,1535]" pageId="8" pageNumber="135">
Habitat and Biology: A widespread eastern species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1863" box="[734,846,1439,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Monotomidae" genus="Hesperobaenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufipes">
<emphasis box="[734,846,1439,1463]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="135">H. rufipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found under bark of hardwood trees (
<taxonomicName authority=", Carya, Fagus, Quercus" authorityName="Carya, Fagus, Quercus" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="135" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="135">Acer, Carya, Fagus, Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) where it eats fungal hyphae, probably mostly Fungi Imperfecti (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[1129,1256,1474,1499]" pageId="8" pageNumber="135" refId="ref6456" refString="Justis, S. (2009) Coleoptera - Hesperobaenus rufipes. Bugguide. net. Iowa State University. Available from: https: // bugguide. net / node / view / 247613 / bgpage (accessed 1 Dec. 2017)" type="url">Justis 2009</bibRefCitation>
). All examined records are from the months of December to May, so it is possible the adults are winter-active.
</paragraph>
